sec.p:
The basic hypothesis of the W-test is that the statistical distributions of a set of disease-associated markers are different in the case group from that in the control group. Under a co-dominant model, the genotype data X can be coded by minor allele count to take values (0, 1, 2). The phenotype Y is binary for the case and control dataset. To test the association of a pair of SNPs (X1, X2), a 2 × 9 contingency table can be formed. Let k denote the number of columns of the table. The cell distribution of (X1, X2) in the case and control group can be written as:
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym} 
\usepackage{amsfonts} 
\usepackage{amssymb} 
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}\begin{equation*}\begin{array}{*{20}{l}} {{{\hat p}_{1i}} = \Pr (X|Y = 1) = \frac{{{n_{1i}}}}{{{N_1}}},}\\ {{{\hat p}_{0i}} = \Pr (X|Y = 0) = \frac{{{n_{0i}}}}{{{N_0}}},\quad \quad i = 1,...,k} \end{array}\end{equation*}\end{document}
where n1i is the number of case subjects in the ith cell, N1 is the total number of cases, n0i is the number of control subjects in the ith cell, and N0 is the total number of controls. For pair-wise interactions, k = 9. The method can also accommodate main effect testing. When a single SNP is considered, k = 3. For both case and control samples, we have:
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym} 
\usepackage{amsfonts} 
\usepackage{amssymb} 
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}\begin{equation*}\sum\limits_{i = 1}^k {{{\hat p}_{1i}} = 1,} \;{\rm{and}}\;\sum\limits_{i = 1}^k {{{\hat p}_{0i}} = 1,} \end{equation*}\end{document}

To measure the discordance between the two distributions, we first use the following measure to combine the normalized log odds ratios of the cell probability distributions:
(1)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym} 
\usepackage{amsfonts} 
\usepackage{amssymb} 
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}\begin{equation*}{X^2} = {\sum\limits_{i = 1}^k {\left[ {{{\log \frac{{{{\hat p}_{1i}}/(1 - {{\hat p}_{1i}})}}{{{{\hat p}_{0i}}/(1 - {{\hat p}_{0i}})}}} \mathord{\left/ {\vphantom {{\log \frac{{{{\hat p}_{1i}}/(1 - {{\hat p}_{1i}})}}{{{{\hat p}_{0i}}/(1 - {{\hat p}_{0i}})}}} {S{E_i}}}} \right.} {S{E_i}}}} \right]} ^2}\end{equation*}\end{document}
where
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym} 
\usepackage{amsfonts} 
\usepackage{amssymb} 
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}\begin{equation*}S{E_i} = \sqrt {\frac{1}{{{n_{0i}}}} + \frac{1}{{{n_{1i}}}} + \frac{1}{{{N_0} - {n_{0i}}}} + \frac{1}{{{N_1} - {n_{1i}}}}} .\end{equation*}\end{document}

Diagram 1 shows the decomposition of X2. Since the contingency table's margins are fixed, the cell probabilities are not entirely independent. If they are independent, the X2 would follow a k degrees of freedom Chi-squared distribution. The mutual dependency among the cells decreases as k becomes large. The distribution of the X2 can be estimated by matching its first two moments to the moments of the following variable R of a known Chi-squared distribution with f degrees of freedom (13):
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym} 
\usepackage{amsfonts} 
\usepackage{amssymb} 
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}\begin{equation*}R = c\chi _f^2\end{equation*}\end{document}

The first two moments of X2 are:
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym} 
\usepackage{amsfonts} 
\usepackage{amssymb} 
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}\begin{equation*}\begin{array}{*{20}{l}} {E({X^2}) = k}\\ {{\sigma ^2}({X^2}) = \sum\limits_i {\sum\limits_j {{\mathop{\rm cov}} (x_i^2,x_j^2)} } = \sum\limits_{i = 1}^k {Var(x_i^2)} + 2\sum\limits_{i < j} {\sum {{\mathop{\rm cov}} (x_i^2,x_j^2)} } }\\ { = 2k + 2\sum\limits_{i < j} {\sum {{\mathop{\rm cov}} (} x_i^2,x_j^2).} } \end{array}\end{equation*}\end{document}
xi and xj are the components in the summation sign in Equation (1), which are the single cell's normalized log of odds ratio. And the first two moments of R are:
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym} 
\usepackage{amsfonts} 
