The W-test is a combined log of odds ratio test based on maximum likelihood probabilities conditioned on disease status. It is equivalent to testing the following null hypothesis:
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym} 
\usepackage{amsfonts} 
\usepackage{amssymb} 
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}\begin{equation*}\begin{array}{*{20}{l}} {{{\rm{H}}_0}:{\rm{P(}}{X_1},{X_2}|Y = 1{\rm{)}} = {\rm{P(}}{X_1},{X_2}|Y = 0{\rm{)}},}\\ {{\rm{such}}\;{\rm{that}}\;O{R_i} = 1,\;{\rm{for}}\;i = 1, \ldots ,k} \end{array}\end{equation*}\end{document}

Model 1. A linear regression model with interaction effect. A linear model can be prescribed by the following logistic regression (18):
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym} 
\usepackage{amsfonts} 
\usepackage{amssymb} 
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}\begin{equation*}LOGIT[P(Y = 1)] = \left\{ {\begin{array}{*{20}{l}} {{\beta _0} + {\beta _1}{X_1} + {\beta _2}{X_2} + {\beta _3}{X_1}{X_2}}&{p = 0.3}\\ {{\beta _4} + {\beta _5}{X_3} + {\beta _6}{X_4} + {\beta _7}{X_3}{X_4}}&{p = 0.3}\\ {\quad \quad \quad \quad \quad \quad {\beta _8}}&{p = 0.4} \end{array}} \right.\end{equation*}\end{document}

Model 2. A non-linear interaction model. The Y has a non-linear association to (X1, X2) and (X3, X4) (19,20):
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym} 
\usepackage{amsfonts} 
\usepackage{amssymb} 
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}\begin{equation*}Y = \left\{ {\begin{array}{*{20}{l}} {{X_1} + {X_2}(\bmod 2)}&{p = 0.3}\\ {{X_3} + {X_4}(\bmod 2)}&{p = 0.3}\\ {\quad \quad \quad 0,1}&{p = 0.4} \end{array}} \right.,\end{equation*}\end{document}
where the Ys are (X1 + X2) mod 2 or (X3 + X4) mod 2 with 30% probability, and are randomly assigned to be 0 or 1 with 40% probability. Only pure interaction effect is present in this model. The null hypothesis is that none of the X predictor is associated with Y.
